"***Question 1: \"How likely is it that Bond will escape from Le Chiffre?\"***\nAnswer: 2. Somewhat likely\n\nAlthough Bond has been caught by Le Chiffre and his gunmen, Bond has shown his agility and quick thinking in trying to escape and exchange words with Vesper. He has also managed to minimize damage to himself when the Corsican tripped him. This suggests that Bond is resourceful and may still have a chance to escape.\n\n***Question 2: \"How suspenseful do you find this passage to be?\"***\nAnswer: 6. Very suspenseful\n\nThe passage is very suspenseful because Bond is in a precarious situation, being held at gunpoint by Le Chiffre's henchmen. The reader is left wondering if Bond will be able to escape or if he will be harmed. The use of words like \"whistle of pain\", \"slammed\", \"crashed\", and \"brusquely\" creates a sense of urgency and tension, adding to the suspense. Additionally, Le Chiffre's ominous phrase \"Let's not waste time\" implies that something ominous is about to happen, further heightening the suspense."